cs.SI, cs.SOC, cs.IR, cs.HC, cs.CL 

This paper examines the social dynamics of content recommendation on the news aggregator Digg, which involves user behavior and social interactions. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.SI (Social and Information Networks). The paper also uses a stochastic model to analyze user behavior, which falls under cs.SOC (Social and Behavioral Sciences). Additionally, the paper discusses content visibility and interestingness, which relates to information retrieval (cs.IR) and human-computer interaction (cs.HC). Finally, the paper mentions evaluating design choices for displaying content, which falls under computational linguistics (cs.CL).
